# NativeWind Styling Rule

Always use NativeWind (Tailwind CSS classes) for styling React Native components instead of inline styles.

## What to use

- Use `className` prop with Tailwind CSS classes
- Example: `className="bg-blue-500 p-4 rounded-lg"`

## What NOT to use

- Avoid inline `style` props with objects
- Avoid hardcoded colors, spacing, etc.

## Examples

✅ **Correct (NativeWind):**

```tsx
<View className="bg-white p-6 rounded-xl shadow-lg">
  <Text className="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Hello World</Text>
</View>
```

❌ **Incorrect (Inline styles):**

```tsx
<View
  style={{
    backgroundColor: "white",
    padding: 24,
    borderRadius: 12,
    shadowColor: "#000",
    shadowOffset: { width: 0, height: 2 },
    shadowOpacity: 0.1,
    shadowRadius: 8,
    elevation: 3,
  }}
>
  <Text
    style={{
      fontSize: 24,
      fontWeight: "bold",
      color: "#1f2937",
      marginBottom: 16,
    }}
  >
    Hello World
  </Text>
</View>
```

## Common NativeWind classes

- **Colors**: `bg-blue-500`, `text-gray-900`, `border-red-200`
- **Spacing**: `p-4`, `m-2`, `px-6`, `py-8`
- **Layout**: `flex`, `flex-row`, `items-center`, `justify-between`
- **Typography**: `text-lg`, `font-bold`, `text-center`
- **Borders**: `border`, `rounded-lg`, `border-gray-300`
- **Shadows**: `shadow-md`, `shadow-lg`

## Files this applies to

- All React Native components (`.tsx` files)
- Web components that should use consistent styling
- Any UI components in the app
